Agarwood is a resinous, odoriferous, and highly valuable heartwood derived from the 

Aquilaria
species

of the 
Thymelaeaceae
family (

). Agarwood is also known as chen-xiang in 
China
, gaharu in 
Indonesia
and 
Malaysia
, jin-koh in 
Japan
, chim-hyuang in 
Korea
, and oud in the Middle East (

). The resin of agarwood is not generated under natural growth conditions, but rather, is formed as a response to injury of the 

Aquilaria

plants caused by natural factors involving animal grazing, lightning strikes, microbial invasions, insect attacks, or artificial manipulations such as physical wounding, chemical wounding, and fungal inoculation (

). The resinous wood is highly prized, which commands an exceptionally high value due to its unique fragrance. Agarwood was first documented in old Indian Sanskrit texts in 1500 B.C.E, and it has aroused a wide spectrum of applications from then on. The medical history of agarwood can be traced back to 65 B.C.E (L´opez-Sampson and 

), it was well-known as a traditional medicine with sedative, analgesic, and carminative effects, and was able to relieve gastric problems, cough, rheumatism, and high fever in modern medicine. Agarwood is widely considered to be a precious raw material of essential oils for aromatherapy and perfumery. It is also utilized as an incense for the holy religious rites and for decorations, as well as in other fields globally (

; 

). Previous phytochemical studies have isolated numerous chemical constituents from agarwood, including sesquiterpenes, 2-(2-phenylethyl)chromone derivatives, aromatics, and triterpenes. Sesquiterpenes and 2-(2-phenylethyl)chromones are the predominant bioactive constituents, accounting for 52% and 41% of the chemical constituents from agarwood, respectively (

). Sesquiterpenes are considered to be important components of the volatile oil, and contribute to the unique aroma of agarwood, where the total content of these compounds may reflect the quality of agarwood to a certain extent. These sesquiterpenes are further classified into eudesmanes, eremophilanes, agarospiranes, agarofurans, guaianes, cadinanes, prezizanes, acoranes, and other skeleton 
types
according to their basic structure (

). Studies have documented numerous bioactivities of the sesquiterpenes isolated from agarwood, including neural activity, gastrointestinal regulation, antibacterial, anti-inflammatory, and cytotoxic effects (

), highlighting the significance to find more active compounds from agarwood.

The absolute configuration of 1 was determined by comparing the experimental and calculated ECD spectra, where the latter were simulated in methanol using the time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) methodology at the CAM-B3LYP/def2-TZVP level. The experimental ECD spectrum of 1 fits well with the calculated ECD spectrum of (2 R , 5 R , 7 R , 10 S )-1 (
Fig. S1.10
). Accordingly, the structure of 1 was determined to be (3 R ,4a S ,7 R ,8a R )-3-hydroxy-7-(3-hydroxyprop-1-en-2- yl)-4a-methyl-3,4,4a,5,6,7,8,8a-octahydronaphthalene-1-carbaldehyde and named agalleudesmanol A.

Compound 5 was obtained as a colourless oil. The molecular formula was determined to be C 15 H 24 O 3 based on HRESIMS [ m/z 270.2059 [M + NH 4 ] + , (calcd. for C 15 H 24 O 3 NH 4 , 270.2069)], indicating four indices of hydrogen deficiency. Comparative analysis of the 1 H and 13 C NMR spectra ( Tables 1 and 3 ) of 4 and 5 revealed that the differences lie in two singlet methyls [ δ H 1.22 (H-12) and δ H 1.24 (H-13)] in 5 instead of an Δ 11,12 double bond and an oxymethylene in 4. This assumption was verified by the HMBC correlations from H 3 -12 ( δ H 1.22) to C-7 ( δ C 48.4)/ C-11 ( δ C 72.9)/C-13 ( δ C 28.0) ( Fig. 2 ). The NOE correlations revealed the relative configuration of C-7, C-9, and C-10 ( Fig. 3 ). Likewise, the absolute configuration of 5 was established by comparing the calculated ECD data with the experimental data. The experimental ECD curves were consistent with the calculated ECD spectra of (7 S , 9 S , 10 S )-5 (
Fig. S5.10
). The structure of 5 was established as (4a S , 5 S , 7 S )-5- hydroxy-7-(2-hydroxypropan-2-yl)-4a-methyl-2,3,4,4a,5,6,7,8-octahy dronaphthalene-1-carbaldehyde and named agalleudesmanol E.

Compound 6 was a colourless oil with the molecular formula of C 15 H 26 O 2 on the basis of its HRESIMS data ([M + NH 4 ] + m/z 256.2273, calcd for C 15 H 26 O 2 NH 4 , 256.2271), and compound 7 possessed the same molecular formula as compound 6 by the analysis of its HRESIMS ([M + NH 4 ] + m/z 256.2272, calcd for C 15 H 26 O 2 NH 4 , 256.2271). The 1D and 2D NMR ( Tables 2 and 3 ) analyses of 6 and 7 suggested that they share the same planar structure ( Fig. 1 and Fig. 2 ) and the same orientations at H-5, H-7, and CH 3 -15 ( Fig. 3 ). The minor differences in the chemical shifts preliminarily suggested that compound 7 was an epimer of 6 at C-11. Because of the present of a flexible exocyclic segment, it was challenging to determine the configuration of all the chiral centers from the NMR data; thus, the relative configuration of 6 and 7 was further confirmed by employing calculations of NMR chemical shifts with support from DP4+ analysis. The probability results from DP4+ analysis also confirmed that compounds 6 and 7 differed in terms of the configuration at C-11, with the probability being 90.65% and 9.35%, respectively (
Fig. S7.10
). In addition, ECD calculation was used to determine the absolute configuration of 6, the experimental ECD curve was in agreement with the calculated ECD spectra of (5 R , 7 R , 10 R, 11 S )- 6 (
Fig. S6.10
). Finally, the structure of 6 was assigned as ( S )-2-((2 R , 4a R , 8a R )-8-(hydroxymethyl)-4a-methyl-1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,8a-octahydronaphthalen-2-yl)propan-1-ol and named agalleudesmanol F; in turn, the structure of 7 was deduced as ( R )-2-((2 R , 4a R , 8a R )-8-(hydroxymethyl)- 4a-methyl-1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,8a.

